<h2>Not Better. Not Worse.</h2>

<p>The temptation on both sides is to claim superiority. Eastern Christians see legalism and liturgical impoverishment in the West. Western Christians see ethnic particularism and institutional dysfunction in the East. Both caricatures contain grains of truth. Both are profoundly unfair.</p>

<p>The healthier posture is gratitude. The West gave the world the university, the hospital, the systematic defense of human rights, and a missionary energy that carried the Gospel to every continent. The East preserved the liturgy in its ancient fullness, developed a theology of the human person that anticipates modern psychology by a millennium, and produced a monastic tradition of breathtaking depth.</p>

<p>Two lungs. One body. The Body of Christ needs both to breathe fully. And perhaps the greatest gift Byzantine Catholics offer the universal Church is the daily, lived experience of holding East and West together. Not in theory. In worship, in prayer, and in the communion of saints.</p>

